 Why Bother?
вҖў Having these methods ensure you have
full control over the instance variables
вҖў Should you decide to change how the
variable is accessed or altered, you only
need to change the method.
вҖў You only add them when you need
them!

 Inter-class Relationships
вҖў Building a single class is useless. It
needs to be used in context.
вҖў There are two main relationships
between classes
вҖ“ Sub/Super class
вҖ“ Ownership

 Subclasses
вҖў A subclass of a class is a more specific
type of a class
вҖў Also known as the child of a class
вҖў For example, a tree would be a subclass
of plant
вҖў Subclasses are meant to expand upon
the behavior of their more general
parent class
вҖў You can have several subclasses

 Superclasses
вҖў On the converse, a superclass is a more
abstract and general version of a class
вҖў Also known as the parent of a class
вҖў Plant is the superclass of Tree
вҖў You can only have one superclass

 Declaring a Class to be a
Subtype
вҖў In order to declare a classвҖҷs parent, use
the keyword extends
вҖў (Classes that do not have a parent class
implicitly extend the Object class)

 Inheritance
вҖў A subclass inherits all non-private fields
and methods
вҖў Accessing these fields and methods
requires the keyword super.
вҖў (Note: you may also be able to access
private fields with the parent classвҖҷs
getters and setters, which may be safer)

 Restricting Access
вҖў What if you want a field or method to be
inherited, but still do not necessarily
want it to be accessed by anyone?
вҖў Use the keyword protected
вҖў Remember, releasing your access to
these fields and methods should only
be done when necessary

 Example
public class Vehicle
{
private final int numWheels;
вҖҰ
public boolean move(double dist)
{
return dist < this.numWheels*10.0;
}//end function(double)
вҖҰ
}//End class Vehicle

 Example A
public class Car extends Vehicle
{
private int numPassengers;
private double gasRemaining;
вҖҰ
public boolean drive(double dist)
{
return (dist < this.numWheels*100.0) &&
(this.gasRemaining > 0);
}//end function(double)
вҖҰ
}//End class Plant

 Example B
public class Car extends Vehicle
{
private int numPassengers;
private double gasRemaining;
вҖҰ
public boolean drive(double dist)
{
return super.move(dist*10.0) &&
(this.gasRemaining > 0);
}//end function(double)
вҖҰ
}//End class Plant

 Which Is Better?
вҖў Example A totally ignores the move
method (essentially its precursor), but is
clearer
вҖў Example B shows the movement
lineage
вҖў Either is okay, but both need
comments!!!!

 Regarding Constructors
вҖў Constructors cannot be inherited, even
though they are public
вҖў However, you can, and should, use them
from the subclassвҖҷs constructor, to
ensure complete initialization
вҖў You can call the parentвҖҷs constructor by
using the keyword super

 Calling Superclass Constructor
вҖў Unlike calling an overloaded
constructor of the same class, calling a
superclass constructor does not need to
be the only line of code
вҖў However, it must still be the first line of
code in the constructor

 Example
public class Vehicle
{
private final int numWheels;
вҖҰ
public Vehicle(int numWheels)
{
this.numWheels = numWheels;
вҖҰ
}//end function(double)
вҖҰ
}//End class Vehicle

 Example
public class Car extends Vehicle
{
private int numPassengers;
private double gasRemaining;
вҖҰ
public Car(int numPassengers, double gasRemaining)
{
super(4);
this.numPassengers = numPassengers;
this.gasRemaining = gasRemaining;
}//end constructor(int,double)
вҖҰ
}//End class Plant

 What If the SuperclassвҖҷs Method
Definition Does Not Fit the ClassвҖҷs?
вҖў We can override the definition by using
the exact same function header
вҖў The line directly above function header
must have вҖң@OverrideвҖқ only
вҖў As an example, our Car class should
probably use the original вҖңmoveвҖқ
method, rather than creating an entirely
new вҖңdriveвҖқ method that does
something similar

 Reminder
public class Car extends Vehicle
{
private int numPassengers;
private double gasRemaining;
вҖҰ
public boolean drive(double dist)
{
return super.move(dist*10.0) &&
(this.gasRemaining > 0);
}//end function(double)
вҖҰ
}//End class Plant

 Override
public class Car extends Vehicle
{
private int numPassengers;
private double gasRemaining;
вҖҰ
@Override
public boolean move(double dist)
{
return super.move(dist*10.0) &&
(this.gasRemaining > 0);
}//end function(double)
вҖҰ
}//End class Plant

 Overriding
вҖў I can still reference the original method
using the super keyword
вҖў Unless your overridden method totally
discards the functionality of the
superclassвҖҷs method, you should call the
superclassвҖҷs method at least once

 Note
вҖў You cannot override constructors

 Ownership
вҖў Ownership is simply one class using
another as a property
вҖў A Car may have an Engine, a Radio, and
an Owner, depending on what you need
вҖў A CarвҖҷs superclass and subclasses
certainly are not Engine, Radio, and
Owner

 Using the Classes
public class Garage
{
private Vehicle[] vehicles;
вҖҰ
public Garage(int capacity)
{
this.vehicles = new Vehicle[capacity];
for(int i = 0; i < vehicles.length; i++)
{
vehicles[i] = null;
}
вҖҰ
}//end constructor(int)
вҖҰ
}//End class Garage

 Using the Classes
public class Garage
{
вҖҰ
public boolean addVehicle(Vehicle vehicle)
{
//Note: there is a better way!
for(int i = 0; i < vehicles.length; i++)
{
if(vehicles[i] == null)
{
vehicles[i] = vehicle;
return true;
}
}
return false;
}//end method(Vehicle)
}//End class Garage

